{"filename":"starship-news","title":"Starship hits two in a row: What SpaceX’s October 13 test means for the next phase","content":"Updated: November 7, 2025

Summary
- SpaceX’s 11th integrated Starship test (IFT-11) lifted off from Starbase, Texas, on October 13, 2025, and met all primary objectives: Super Heavy made a controlled water landing in the Gulf of Mexico and the Starship upper stage splashed down in the Indian Ocean after a suborbital hop roughly an hour later. The flight also deployed eight Starlink simulators and tested heat shield and guidance upgrades. citeturn1news12turn1news13turn1search3
- The success marked SpaceX’s second consecutive full-mission win following a string of mishaps earlier in 2025, closing out the current “Version 2” test article before an upgraded configuration debuts. citeturn1news13
- Separately, the FAA this year expanded Starship’s permitted cadence from five to as many as 25 launches per year from Texas, a key enabler for higher flight tempo as SpaceX transitions to the next variant. citeturn0search0

What flew on IFT‑11
Starship IFT‑11 lifted off on the evening of October 13, 2025, from Starbase. After stage separation, the Super Heavy booster executed its descent and soft splashdown in the Gulf of Mexico. The Starship upper stage continued downrange, performed on‑orbit objectives, then reentered and splashed down in the Indian Ocean about 66 minutes after liftoff. SpaceX also released eight mock Starlink payloads to exercise deployment systems and in‑space operations. Multiple outlets — including AP and Reuters — reported that SpaceX declared all primary goals achieved. citeturn1news12turn1news13

What was new
- Thermal‑protection stress tests: SpaceX intentionally exposed select areas of the vehicle to higher heating to collect data on tile performance and margins headed into the next hardware iteration. citeturn1search6
- Guidance and control refinements: The ship executed a dynamic banking turn during reentry to simulate future targeted returns, part of the roadmap toward controlled landings. citeturn1news14
- Reuse milestones: The booster used previously flown hardware, extending Starship’s reusability demonstrations beyond Falcon‑class vehicles. citeturn1search3

Why it matters
Back‑to‑back successes — August’s IFT‑10 and October’s IFT‑11 — turn the page on a year that began with high‑profile mishaps and temporary grounding. FAA licensing steps and mishap reviews shaped the schedule through mid‑year, but by fall SpaceX had restored mission confidence with two end‑to‑end flights that hit their test cards. That progress is foundational for three near‑term goals: raising flight cadence, introducing the upgraded vehicle, and advancing NASA’s Human Landing System (HLS) milestones. citeturn2news12turn0news13

Policy and cadence
In May, the FAA’s environmental decision increased the allowable annual Starship launches from Starbase to as many as 25, removing a structural cap that previously limited operations to five. While each flight still requires licensing and safety reviews, the higher ceiling reduces friction as SpaceX aims for more frequent testing and rapid iteration in 2026. citeturn0search0

What’s next: the upgraded Starship
IFT‑11 was widely described as the final mission of the current “V2” hardware before SpaceX debuts an upgraded configuration with changes aimed at deep‑space objectives. Expect visible updates to structures, thermal protection, and avionics, plus under‑the‑hood changes to support on‑orbit engine relights and, eventually, propellant transfer. SpaceX‑focused trade and specialist outlets note the company’s plan to roll this upgraded ship as the program pivots from mere survivability to repeatability. citeturn1news13

NASA’s lunar path and a ‘simplified’ approach
NASA’s Artemis landings depend on a Starship‑derived HLS. Following the October flight, SpaceX outlined work on a “simplified” lunar mission architecture intended to accelerate crewed lunar return while improving safety, though details and timelines remain sparse. Independent reporting highlighted that SpaceX is reassessing how many in‑space refueling events are required, and the company has showcased additional HLS development work. Any shift here could materially change the tempo and complexity of tanker flights needed ahead of a landing demonstration. citeturn2search0turn2search5

Open questions for 2026
- Orbital refueling demos: HLS hinges on cryogenic propellant transfer between Starships. SpaceX and NASA have long targeted initial on‑orbit transfer tests in the 2025–2026 timeframe; with IFT‑11 complete, eyes turn to when those demos will occur on upgraded hardware. citeturn2search3
- Controlled landings: The next major leap is moving from water splashdowns to controlled surface or pad landings for both stages. The guidance work in IFT‑10/11 is a precursor, but a full recovery attempt remains ahead. citeturn1search3
- Cape expansion: Alongside Texas operations, SpaceX continues preparing Florida facilities for future Starship flights, a move that could diversify launch options as cadence increases. (This is an inference based on agency and media briefings around facility upgrades.) citeturn1news12

The bottom line
On October 13, 2025, Starship delivered a second straight clean test, validating fixes and building momentum at a program level. With the FAA’s cadence expansion in place and a new hardware generation queued up, the next phase will be defined by higher flight rates, on‑orbit propellant transfer, and progressively more exacting recovery tests — the stepping stones from splashdowns to operational lunar landings. citeturn0search0turn1news13"}
